      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm editing a biology paper and i keep seeing a lot of passive voice. can u explain how to spot it and how i should actually fix it so the sentences are more direct?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Passive voice can be a sneaky thing, but spotting it is relatively easy. It's often marked by the subject of the sentence coming after the verb, rather than the other way around. For example, \"The experiment was conducted by John\" is passive voice, while \"John conducted the experiment\" is active voice. To fix it, try to move the subject to the beginning of the sentence, making it the first thing the reader sees. This will make the sentence more direct and easier to follow.",
